That looks a lot simpler, dad
I guess I went into too much realism, with gravity and everything, and not a simple quadratic arc:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------- -- Initializations function modifier_generic_knockback_lua:OnCreated( kv ) if IsServer() then --/--/--/--/-- -- vertical init local half_duration = self.duration/2 self.gravity = 2*self.height/(half_duration*half_duration) self.vVelocity = self.gravity*half_duration --/--/--/--/-- if self.height>=0 then if self:ApplyVerticalMotionController() == false then self:Destroy() return end end --/--/--/-- end end --/--/--/--/-- -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- -- Motion effects function modifier_generic_knockback_lua:UpdateVerticalMotion( me, dt ) -- set time local time = dt/self.duration -- change height self.parent:SetOrigin( self.parent:GetOrigin() + Vector( 0, 0, self.vVelocity*dt ) ) -- calculate vertical velocity self.vVelocity = self.vVelocity - self.gravity*dt end

Toyoka 29-May-19 01:26 PM
in which case I recommend to either: a) just oscillate its scale and fuck the animation altogether or b) oscillate the animaition so that it reaches the middle of the "beat" animation and oscillates backwards to the start of the animation, instead of playing the full animation with a pause (this is a bit more difficult to achieve)
there's a bunch of properties here in the model renderer https://i.imgur.com/CJLSHCA.png
you want to focus on one of these https://i.imgur.com/GAM97c1.png https://i.imgur.com/D58bryk.png
the default values for these (trail length and creation time) are scalar properties
I believe the first of the two is what can be oscillated
(or should be oscillated, rather)
actually no I'm wrong, that would change the speed dynamically
you probably want the "beat" constant
you want the frames to oscillate
you can change the "creation time" field to "trail length" and the animation rate scale field to something you won't use (or just set it to NONE/disabled https://i.imgur.com/sBmRdNT.png)
(it doesn't have to be trail length btw, it's whatever you want it to be, but just to make this easier, set it as that)
